                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.841 Surtax/36: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-08-26T18:00:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 26, 1927—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department has been shown cable of August 23 from Shanghai office U. S. Steel
                    Products Company reading in part “Have cleared S. S. <hi rend="italic">Mobile
                        City</hi> without payment illegal 25 per cent surtax tonnage dues on the
                    advice American Consul.”</p>
                <p>Department’s telegram to you of August 17, 3 p.m., did not instruct you to advise
                    steamship owners not to pay tonnage surtax. Question should be left to decision
                    of Steamship Company at whose risk clearance is given.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
